            . I am a <rs id="t18320906-215-viclabel1213" type="occupation">carpenter</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18320906-215-victim1778 t18320906-215-viclabel1213"></join>, and live in Henry-street East, Bedford-square. On the evening of the 24th of July, I was walking in <placeName id="t18320906-215-crimeloc1214">High-street, St. Giles'</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18320906-215-crimeloc1214" type="placeName" value="High-street, St. Giles'"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18320906-215-crimeloc1214" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18320906-215-off1211 t18320906-215-crimeloc1214"></join> - I saw Knowles in the custody of Stone; I felt my pocket, and missed my handkerchief, which I saw in Stone's hand.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18320906-215-person1780">
                  GEORGE 
                  STONE
               <interp inst="t18320906-215-person1780" type="surname" value="STONE"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18320906-215-person1780" type="given" value="GEORGE"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18320906-215-person1780" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             (Police-constable C 99). On the 24th of July, between eight and nine o'clock in the evening, I was in High-street, and saw the two prisoners together at the corner of Oxford-street - when Mr. Brown passed they followed him to the church, when Knowles put his hand in and picked his pocket - Williams was close to him at the time; I went in between them, and secured Knowles; he put his hand behind him, as if to give the handkerchief to Williams, but I took it, and Williams ran off.</p>
               <p>Knowles. You swore that Williams was several yards from me; you are not the man who took me, it was a man in plain clothes. Witness. We were both in plain clothes- Williams was close to you; they were both very desperate indeed; they laid on the ground, and said they would not go.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18320906-215-person1781">
                  THOMAS 
                  FARRANT
               <interp inst="t18320906-215-person1781" type="surname" value="FARRANT"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18320906-215-person1781" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18320906-215-person1781" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             (Police-constable C 42). I was with Stone, and pursued Williams - he made great resistance, and fought terribly; I got him into a public-house, and when I had handcuffed him I went out to assist Stone - they raised a mob of five or six hundred persons; the prosecutor was forced to assist to get them along.</p>
               <p>KNOWLES - <rs id="t18320906-215-verdict1215" type="verdictDescription">
